{{Italic title}} {{Taxobox | name = ''Bombali ebolavirus'' | virus_group = v | ordo = ''[[Mononegavirales]]'' | familia = ''[[Filoviridae]]'' | genus = ''[[Ebolavirus]]'' | species = ''unassigned'' | subdivision_ranks = Member virus (Abbreviation) | subdivision = }}
'''''Bombali ebolavirus''''' is a newly discovered strain of ''[[Ebolavirus]],'' first reported on 27 July 2018.<ref>{{cite web | title=Ministry of Health Sierra Leone |url=http://www.thesierraleonetelegraph.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/07/Ministry-of-Health-Sierra-Leone-new-strain-of-Ebola-virus-found.pdf | accessdate=27 July 2018}}</ref> It was discovered by a research team from the U.S. in the western Africa country of [[Sierra Leone]].<ref>{{cite web | title=New Ebola species is reported for first time in a decade - STAT | url=https://www.statnews.com/2018/07/27/ebola-virus-discovery/ | website=statnews.com | accessdate=27 July 2018 | date=27 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=New Ebola virus strain found in Sierra Leone | url=https://reliefweb.int/report/sierra-leone/new-ebola-virus-strain-found-sierra-leone | website=reliefweb.int | accessdate=27 July 2018 | language=en}}</ref> The [[virus]] was found in the [[Angolan free-tailed bat]] and the [[Little free-tailed bat]].<ref>{{cite web | last1=Rosenbaum | first1=Leah | title=A new Ebola species has been found in bats in Sierra Leone | url=https://www.sciencenews.org/blog/science-ticker/new-ebola-virus-species-bats-sierra-leone | website=sciencenews.org | accessdate=28 July 2018 | language=en | date=27 July 2018}}</ref> ''Bombali ebolavirus'' has the capacity to infect [[human cells]], although it had not yet been shown to be pathogenic.<ref>{{cite web | title=New Ebola virus found in Sierra Leone, govt says | url=https://punchng.com/new-ebola-virus-found-in-sierra-leone-govt-says/ | website=punchng.com | accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Scientists in West Africa are warning that a new strain of Ebola could infect humans. | url=https://www.newsweek.com/scientists-warn-new-ebola-strain-found-west-africa-has-potential-infect-1046701 | website=newsweek.com |accessdate=28 July 2018 | language=en | date=28 July 2018}}</ref>
==Species organization and history== [[File:Filovirus phylogenetic tree.svg|330px|thumb|[[Phylogenetic tree]] comparing ebolaviruses and marburgviruses. Numbers indicate percent confidence of branches(prior to Bombali ebolavirus discovery)]] [[File:Ebola virus em.jpg|thumb|90 px|left|Ebola virus 1976]]
''Ebolavirus'' and ''[[Marburgvirus]]'' are genera in the family [[Filoviridae]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Kuhn | first1=Jens H. | last2=Becker | first2=Stephan | last3=Ebihara | first3=Hideki | last4=Geisbert | first4=Thomas W. | last5=Johnson | first5=Karl M. | last6=Kawaoka | first6=Yoshihiro | last7=Lipkin | first7=W. Ian | last8=Negredo | first8=Ana I. | last9=Netesov | first9=Sergey V. | last10=Nichol | first10=Stuart T. | last11=Palacios | first11=Gustavo | last12=Peters | first12=Clarence J. | last13=Tenorio | first13=Antonio | last14=Volchkov | first14=Viktor E. | last15=Jahrling | first15=Peter B. | title=Proposal for a revised taxonomy of the family Filoviridae: classification, names of taxa and viruses, and virus abbreviations |journal=Archives of Virology |date=December 2010 | volume=155 | issue=12 | pages=2083–2103 | doi=10.1007/s00705-010-0814-x | pmc=3074192 | issn=0304-8608}}</ref>
In 1976 in [[Sudan]], ''[[Sudan ebolavirus]]'' became the first species of ''Ebolavirus'' to be discovered.<ref>{{cite journal | title=Ebola haemorrhagic fever in Sudan, 1976 | journal=[[Bulletin of the World Health Organization]] | year=1978 | volume=56 | issue=2 | pages=247–270 | pmc=2395561 | issn=0042-9686| author1=Report of a WHO/International Study Team }}</ref> Later that year, the ''[[Zaire ebolavirus]]'' species was discovered.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Breman | first1=Joel G. | last2=Heymann | first2=David L. | last3=Lloyd | first3=Graham | last4=McCormick | first4=Joseph B. | last5=Miatudila | first5=Malonga | last6=Murphy | first6=Frederick A. | last7=Muyembé-Tamfun | first7=Jean-Jacques | last8=Piot | first8=Peter | last9=Ruppol | first9=Jean-François | last10=Sureau | first10=Pierre | last11=van der Groen | first11=Guido | last12=Johnson | first12=Karl M. | title=Discovery and Description of Ebola Zaire Virus in 1976 and Relevance to the West African Epidemic During 2013–2016 | journal=[[Journal of Infectious Diseases]] | date=29 June 2016 | volume=214 | issue=suppl 3 | pages=S93–S101 | doi=10.1093/infdis/jiw207 | url=https://academic.oup.com/jid/article-abstract/214/suppl_3/S93/2388104?redirectedFrom=fulltext | accessdate=28 July 2018 | language=en | issn=0022-1899}}Subscription required</ref>
In 1989, the ''[[Reston ebolavirus]]'' species was discovered in the Philippines<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Miranda | first1=Mary E. G. |last2=White | first2=Mark E. | last3=Dayrit | first3=Manuel M. | last4=Hayes | first4=Curtis G. | last5=Ksiazek | first5=Thomas G. | last6=Burans | first6=James P. | title=Seroepidemiological study of filovirus related to Ebola in the Philippines | journal=[[The Lancet]] | date=February 1991 | volume=337 | issue=8738 | pages=425–426 | doi=10.1016/0140-6736(91)91199-5 | url=https://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PII0140-6736(91)91199-5/abstract | accessdate=28 July 2018 | language=English | issn=0140-6736}}{{Subscription or libraries|sentence|via=[[ScienceDirect]]}}</ref> (the U.S. would later be introduced to the strain in quarantine) however no fatalities occurred though 4 people developed [[antibodies]] to the virus.<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Geisbert | first1=T. W | last2=Jahrling | first2=P. B. | title=Use of immunoelectron microscopy to show Ebola virus during the 1989 United States epizootic. | journal=[[Journal of Clinical Pathology]] | date=October 1990 | volume=43 | issue=10 | pages=813–816 | pmc=502829 | issn=0021-9746}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Epidemiologic Notes and ReportsUpdate: Filovirus Infection in Animal Handlers | url=https://www.cdc.gov/mmwr/preview/mmwrhtml/00001593.htm |website=www.cdc.gov | accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | date=3 March 1990 | title=Preliminary report: isolation of Ebola virus from monkeys imported to USA | url=https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/014067369090737P | journal=[[The Lancet]] | language=en | volume=335 | issue=8688 | pages=502–505 | doi=10.1016/0140-6736(90)90737-P|issn=0140-6736| last1=Jahrling | first1=P.B | last2=Geisbert | first2=T.W | last3=Johnson | first3=E.D | last4=Peters | first4=C.J | last5=Dalgard | first5=D.W | last6=Hall | first6=W.C }}</ref>
The ''[[Taï Forest ebolavirus]]'' species was discovered in 1995 in [[Ivory Coast]].<ref>{{cite journal | last1=Le Guenno | first1=B. | last2=Formenty | first2=P. | last3=Formentry | first3=P. | last4=Wyers | first4=M. | last5=Gounon | first5=P. | last6=Walker | first6=F. | last7=Boesch | first7=C. | title=Isolation and partial characterisation of a new strain of Ebola virus | journal=[[The Lancet]] | date=20 May 1995 | volume=345 | issue=8960 | pages=1271–1274 | pmid=7746057 | issn=0140-6736}}</ref>
The ''[[Bundibugyo ebolavirus]]'' species was discovered during an outbreak in Uganda in 2007 that had a mortality rate of 40 percent.<ref>{{Cite journal| last1=MacNeil | first1=Adam | last2=Farnon | first2=Eileen C. | last3=Wamala | first3=Joseph | last4=Okware | first4=Sam | last5=Cannon | first5=Deborah L. | last6=Reed | first6=Zachary | last7=Towner | first7=Jonathan S. | last8=Tappero | first8=Jordan W. | last9=Lutwama | first9=Julius | last10=Downing | first10=Robert | last11=Nichol | first11=Stuart T. | last12=Ksiazek | first12=Thomas G. | last13=Rollin | first13=Pierre E. | title=Proportion of Deaths and Clinical Features in Bundibugyo Ebola Virus Infection, Uganda | journal=Emerging Infectious Diseases | volume=16 | issue=12 | url=https://wwwnc.cdc.gov/eid/article/16/12/10-0627_article | pages=1969–1972 | language=en-us |doi=10.3201/eid1612.100627 | date=December 2010}}</ref>
